<subSubSection lastPageId="10" lastPageNumber="42" pageId="9" pageNumber="41" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,1815,1999]" pageId="9" pageNumber="41">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,279,1815,1841]" pageId="9" pageNumber="41">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Predominantly black specimens. Scutum with few setae, pleurae with dark yellow spots. 
<collectingCountry box="[1334,1393,1816,1842]" name="India" pageId="9" pageNumber="41">Hind</collectingCountry>
leg black, except basal half of femur yellow; tibiae and tarsi darkened. 
<collectingCountry box="[958,1017,1854,1880]" name="India" pageId="9" pageNumber="41">Hind</collectingCountry>
tibia bearing 
<number box="[1184,1199,1854,1880]" pageId="9" pageNumber="41" value="1.0">1</number>
strong anterodorsal bristle. Veins R 
<number box="[331,339,1909,1923]" pageId="9" pageNumber="41" value="4.0">4</number>
+ 
<number box="[348,356,1909,1923]" pageId="9" pageNumber="41" value="5.0">5</number>
and M bowed in apical half of the wing.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1436,1815,1999]" pageId="9" pageNumber="41">
In the following, we update the redescription of 
<bibRefCitation author="Rafael" box="[738,908,1935,1961]" pageId="9" pageNumber="46" refString="Rafael, J. A. (1995) Revisao das especies Neotropicais de Empididae (Diptera) descritas por Mario Bezzi. II. Tachydromiinae. Revista Brasileira de Entomologia, 39, 733 - 739." type="journal article" year="1995">
Rafael (
<number box="[834,899,1935,1961]" pageId="9" pageNumber="41" value="1995.0">1995</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
, presenting characters nowadays utilized in taxonomy of this group. We also update the terminology utilized.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="10.[151,1438,151,1617]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[198,382,151,177]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42">Re-description</emphasis>
. 
<typeStatus box="[401,518,152,178]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42">Lectotype</typeStatus>
female. Anterior ocellar setae proclinate, long, cruciate, posterior pair lost. Pedicel with circlet of short setulae. Thorax with dark yellow spots on postalar callus, upper posterior corner and posterior margin of anepisternum, katepisternum and anepimeron; scutum slightly longer than wide, narrow on anterior part, 
<number box="[446,484,268,294]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="6.2">6.2</number>
times longer than scutellum, with few yellow setae, conspicuous setae reddish yellow. Proepisternum bearing 
<number box="[515,530,306,332]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="1.0">1</number>
long seta on upper part, lacking setae just above fore coxa; postpronotal setae prominent; 
<number box="[290,305,345,371]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="2.0">2</number>
notopleural setae (posterior one longer than anterior); 
<number box="[967,982,345,371]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="3.0">3</number>
supra-alar setae; 
<number box="[1195,1210,345,371]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="1.0">1</number>
very long postalar seta. Acrostichals apparently in 
<number box="[540,555,384,410]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="2.0">2</number>
complete rows; dorsocentrals distinct from intra-alars, 
<number box="[1228,1243,384,410]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="2.0">2</number>
complete rows, prescutellar seta long. Fore tarsomeres 
<number box="[609,652,422,448]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="3.0" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="2.0">2–4</number>
bearing numerous short ventral setulae. Mid femur with numerous spinule-like ventral bristles. Mid tibia with ventral spinules. 
<collectingCountry box="[859,918,461,487]" name="India" pageId="10" pageNumber="42">Hind</collectingCountry>
tibia bearing 
<number box="[1079,1094,461,487]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="1.0">1</number>
long anterodorsal bristle and broad and short apical projection. Wing (
<figureCitation box="[644,731,500,526]" captionStart="FIGURES 16 – 19" captionStartId="13.[151,272,941,965]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,351,914]" captionTargetId="figure@13.[151,1436,351,914]" captionTargetPageId="13" captionText="FIGURES 16 – 19. Wings. 16. Elaphropeza biseticauda (Smith, 1963) [3 from Brazil, basal seta not presented]. 17. Elaphropeza flavida (Williston, 1896) [3 from Brazil, basal seta not presented]. 18. Elaphropeza mazaruni (Smith, 1963) [3 from Brazil, basal seta not presented]. 19. Elaphropeza monochaeta (Bezzi, 1909) [lectotype Ƥ]. Scale = 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/190686/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="42">
Fig. 
<number box="[701,731,500,526]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="19.0">19</number>
</figureCitation>
) with costal index: 
<number box="[971,1001,500,526]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="45.0">45</number>
/ 
<number box="[1011,1041,500,526]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="25.0">25</number>
/ 
<number box="[1051,1082,500,526]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="32.0">32</number>
/ 
<number box="[1091,1119,500,526]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="19.0">19</number>
; Rs somewhat longer than cross-vein bm-cu, R 
<number box="[389,397,554,568]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="2.0">2</number>
+ 
<number box="[407,414,554,568]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="3.0">3</number>
arched reaching C in apical third of wing, R 
<number box="[943,951,554,568]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="4.0">4</number>
+ 
<number box="[961,968,554,568]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="5.0">5</number>
and M somewhat bowed in apical half, parallels from each other near margin; CuA 
<number box="[660,668,596,610]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="1.0">1</number>
reaching wing margin; A 
<number box="[967,975,596,610]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="1.0">1</number>
inconspicuous. Basal medial cell twice longer and wider than basal radial cell; cross-vein bm-cu forming acute angle with CuA 
<number box="[1230,1238,637,651]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="1.0">1</number>
. Abdomen with tergites 
<number box="[250,296,663,689]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="1.5" valueMax="2.0" valueMin="1.0">1–2</number>
and all sternites pale yellow, almost white; tergite 
<number box="[931,946,663,689]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="3.0">3</number>
reddish, darker than other; tergites 
<number box="[1391,1437,663,689]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="6.0" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="5.0">5–7</number>
somewhat pale yellow in middle. Tergites 
<number box="[661,705,702,728]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="3.5" valueMax="4.0" valueMin="3.0">3–4</number>
with short squamiform setae laterally. Segment 
<number box="[1288,1303,702,728]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="8.0">8</number>
short (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 13 – 15. 13" captionStartId="12.[151,277,1101,1125]" captionTargetBox="[436,1152,368,1061]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[415,1171,351,1076]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 13 – 15. 13. Elaphropeza monochaeta (Bezzi, 1909) [lectotype Ƥ]. Ovipositor, lateral view. 14 – 15. Elaphropeza similis (Smith, 1963) [holotype 3]. 14. Right epandrial lamella, lateral view. 15. Epandrium with cerci (short setae on left surstylus omitted), dorsal view. Scale = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/190685/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="42">
Fig. 
<number box="[151,182,740,766]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="13.0">13</number>
</figureCitation>
), sclerites separated, sternite lacking lateral projection; sternite 
<number box="[933,962,740,766]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="10.0">10</number>
as in 
<figureCitation box="[1034,1117,740,766]" captionStart="FIGURES 9 – 12" captionStartId="8.[151,271,1870,1894]" captionTargetBox="[194,1400,758,1822]" captionTargetId="figure@8.[151,1436,747,1846]" captionTargetPageId="8" captionText="FIGURES 9 – 12. Elaphropeza mazaruni (Smith, 1963) [9 – 11. Holotype 3]. 9. Epandrium with cerci, dorsal view. 10. Right epandrial lamella, lateral view. 11. Left surstylus, lateral view. 12. [Ƥ from Brazil] Ovipositor, lateral view. Scale = 0.1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/190684/files/figure.png" pageId="10" pageNumber="42">
Fig. 
<number box="[1088,1117,740,766]" pageId="10" pageNumber="42" value="12.0">12</number>
</figureCitation>
[ovipositor was macerated and was not possible to observe colour of cercus].
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
